entry.title: Settings: Restamp basic page so that prefs subproperty changes propagate
entry.content:
https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5014869 fixed

an issue with the logic to show the settings basicPage. As a result the

dom-if for basicPage is now false when the current route is not set to

a route in the basic page (e.g. chrome://settings/reset).



Due to the way Polymer data bindings work inside dom-ifs, this meant

that prefs subproperty changes no longer triggered observers to fire,

so when settings like the theme were reset from

chrome://settings/reset, these changes were not correctly reflected in

the DOM even after the basic page dom-if flipped back to true (e.g.

after navigating to the appearance settings).



See https://github.com/Polymer/polymer/issues/4818 for additional

context on this Polymer behavior.



Fixing by using a restamp on the dom-if to force a rerender when it

changes from false to true.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Refactor `AutocompleteController`
entry.content:
go/autocomplete-controller-refactor has some details on the refactor

plan.



This is part 5 of the refactor.



- Split `UpdateResult()` into helpers. E.g. `AggregateNewMatches()`. The

goal is readers can look at `UpdateResult()` and get a outline of what

it does without having to scroll through code. This call hierarchy is

a bit flatter than before; e.g. helper 1 doesn't call helper 2 which

then calls helper 3.



- Remove `done_` and `sync_pass_done_` internal states. Before, it was

difficult to know what each `AutocompleteController()` method would

do, because their behaviors depended both on the params passed in and

the controllers internal state. So a reader would have to backstep to

figure out what the internal state was for each call path. Now, the

behavior of `UpdateResult()` & `DelayedNotifyChanged()` depend on

their parameters only. `done_` and `sync_pass_done_` were also unclear

because the former refers to the providers being done but not the

controller, whereas the latter refers to the controller being done.



- Add `last_update_type_` field. We still need internal state because

other objects need to know what autocomplete state the controller is

in. But it's not used internally by the controller itself (see above

bullet).



- Centralize some logic into `UpdateResult()`. Specifically, the stop &

expire timers are now started and stopped here instead of being

manipulated throughout the class. Also centralized here is determining

whether to run an immediate or delayed notification.



- Add extensive tests. Autocompletion is pretty nuanced; it

conditionally transfers old matches, debounces, runs expire & stop

timers, ML reranks, or preserves the default match. None of this

behavior was tested, despite how critical they were. This CL adds

extensive tests.



- Update `AutocompleteControllerMetrics` to look at `last_update_type_`

instead of the now removed `done_` and `sync_pass_done_`. It becomes a

bit simpler too.



- Update `AutocompleteControllerMetrics` tests to actually run the

controller to make sure the integration works. E.g., before, tests

would call `metrics.X(); metrics.Y()` and verify the correct metrics

were recorded. Now, the tests call `controller.A()` and verify `A()`

actually calls `X()` and `Y()` and the correct metrics are recorded.



Low-Coverage-Reason: OTHER This CL adds tests to previously untested

code. The coverage checker is looking at an iOS file that this CL

touched but is not the focus of this CL. And I'm unsure if the coverage

checker works with iOS files?

entry.title: firmware_update: Add FwupdRequest and observer [reland]
entry.content:
[Note: this CL is a reland of https://crrev.com/c/5123878 that fixes a

memory leak caused by using the `new` keyword. The original CL is

patchset 1 of this CL, so you can view the diff here:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5141688/1..6]

[I've confirmed that this fixes the memory leak by running

"linux_chromium_chromeos_asan_rel_ng". You can see the build here:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/try/linux_chromium_chromeos_asan_rel_ng/18274/overview]



This CL adds a struct called FwupdRequest that will be used to hold

request data that comes from the fwupd D-Bus signal "DeviceRequest".



This CL also adds a new virtual method to the Observer class within

FwupdClient called "OnDeviceRequestResponse". This CL also implements

entry.title: Sync network state for AlwaysOnVpnPreConnectUrlAllowlist usage with Lacros
entry.content:
The AlwaysOnVpnPreConnectUrlAllowlist policy defines URL filters that

are used in Lacros to determine the URLs where the user can navigate

to before an Always-on VPN connects.



This policy should be enforced in Lacros when:

- the policy is not empty

- a Always-on VPN is configured in lockdown mode

- the VPN is not connected



The state of the AlwaysOnVpnPreConnectUrlAllowlist usage is determined

in Ash. This CL syncs this state with the Lacros browser instances via

the NetworkSettingsService mojo crosapi.



Bug: b/259497264

entry.title: [chromedriver] Ignore nonexistent windows in `window/handles`
entry.content:
`chromedriver` implements webdriver classic's "Get Window Handles"

endpoint [0] using CDP's `Target.getTargets`, followed by enumerating

new web views with `Target.attachToTarget` [1, 2].



However, a browsing context returned from `getTargets` may `close()`

itself [3] before `chromedriver` attaches to it, which returns "no such

window" to the `chromedriver` client (contrary to the spec). In this CL,

assume "newly created" windows may not exist because of this race and

simply don't process them.



[0]: https://www.w3.org/TR/webdriver2/#get-window-handles

[1]: https://chromedevtools.github.io/devtools-protocol/tot/Target/

[2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/test/chromedriver/chrome/chrome_impl.cc;l=125-126;drc=8e78783dc1f7007bad46d657c9f332614e240fd8;bpv=0;bpt=1

[3]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/web_tests/external/wpt/html/anonymous-iframe/resources/embedding-test.js;l=37-39;drc=6445759719756538840d3af83fc798daeec4995e;bpv=0;bpt=0
